📜 LSAAR Laboratory Contribution & Policy Guidelines
Welcome to the LSAAR Research Group. To ensure research reproducibility, code quality, and efficient collaboration, all members (PhD and MSc students) must adhere to the following guidelines.

1. Repository Naming Conventions
Every new project must follow our standardized naming prefix:

opt-: For projects primarily focused on Structural Optimization.

ai-: For projects primarily focused on Artificial Intelligence / Machine Learning.

core-: For shared libraries, tools, or documentation used by the entire lab.

Example: ai-seismic-damage-detection or opt-truss-topology-optimization.

2. Standardized Folder Structure
To keep our workspace clean, every repository should use the following directory layout:

/src: All source code (scripts, classes, modules).

/data: Small datasets and sample files (CSV, JSON).

/notebooks: Jupyter notebooks or experimental scripts.

/docs: Research notes, papers (LaTeX), and presentations.

/results: Output logs, figures, and trained model weights.

3. Data Management & File Size Limits
GitHub is not a storage drive for raw big data.

Strict Limit: Never upload individual files larger than 50MB.

Hard Block: GitHub will reject any file over 100MB.

Solution: For large datasets, upload them to the lab's official Cloud/Server and provide a download link or a download_data.sh script in your repository.

4. Reproducibility & Environments
A project is only complete if someone else can run it.

Every repository must include a dependency file:

requirements.txt (for pip/Python)

environment.yml (for Conda)

Project.toml (for Julia)

Include a README.md with clear instructions on how to set up and run the code.

5. Git Best Practices
Commit Often: Push your progress at least once a week to ensure a cloud backup of your research.

Meaningful Messages: Avoid messages like "update" or "fix". Use descriptive titles like "Added Adam optimizer to the AI model".

Branching: Use branches for new experiments to keep the main branch stable.

6. Offboarding
Before completing your degree or leaving the lab:

Ensure all your code is pushed to the LSAAR Organization.

Update your documentation so the next researcher can continue your work.

Notify the Lab Administrator ([Your Name]) to archive your repository.

For any technical issues or access requests, contact the Lab Administrator.
